<br>
Role play is not limited to strict classic models, diversity can make things even more intersting...a character that is role-played as a vampyre, another some other type of undead.   A Vah Shir as a Kerrin.  Etc.  Imagination can enrich the game greatly.  <br>
So EQ calls Hobbits Halfings.  So does D&amp;D now.  <br>
Dark elves are called Drow in D&amp;D.<br>
Drow is to Teir'dal as 'Indian' is to the Native American Tribes.  A generic term, and possable slang, depending upon how one views it.<br>
  <br>
Dark elves are called Teir'Dal Formally.  It is the stuck up ones that have a problem with 'Drow' as a term for our race.  <br>
As for the spider queen, well, seeing how there are halfspider half dark elves in existance, perhaps somewhere some Teir'Dal worship one as their queen.  A sub cult, or a parallel universe.  This dark elf cares not, other than to note that Mayong Mistmoore origionally created the spider beings.<br>
<br>
As for patriarchal or matriarchal, we have both a queen and a king, and they are somewhat at odds with each other.  The Mistress at the head of the warrior guild has made it clear that she struggled hard and long for her position, she EARNED it.  The guildmasters for the shadowknight and necromancer guilds are male.   While it is somewhat harder for the wemon in our society to earn their positions, the society as a whole is more of a gender neutral aspect. <br>
<br>
Roleplaying is how you develope the background and personality of your character and act it out, with the relationships of your enviroment.  It is not sticking with someone else's predefined rules of how your character should fit in.  After all, some will be loyal to a racial cause, others will be outcast.<br>
<br>
Oh, and Lethe, if you write, why don't you also come on over and join us in the Harpy's Head tavern.  We could use a few more good, and dedicated long term writers.<br>
<br>
